## Levin as the base

Michael Levin is the best primary science base because he refuses the idea that “mind = brain only.” His TAME framework treats agency as something that can appear across many substrates and scales, from cells to tissues to organisms to possible artificial/hybrid systems. It asks how to recognize and compare diverse intelligences rather than assuming cognition only exists in human brains. ([Frontiers][1])

His key idea for your framework is the **cognitive light cone**: a self/agent is defined by the scale of goals it can sense, model, and act upon. In his “Computational Boundary of a Self” paper, a self is demarcated by the spatiotemporal boundary of events it can measure, model, and affect. ([Frontiers][2])

That maps directly onto your Selfing Loop.

A sub-agent is not “fake.” It is a **local goal-system** with a small cognitive light cone.

An anxious appeaser-part has a tiny light cone:

> “avoid rejection now.”

A higher daimonic/HGA pattern has a larger light cone:

> “shape this life toward its true form.”

A Buddha/deity/angelic-function has an even larger symbolic light cone:

> “organize body, speech, mind, and world toward compassion/wisdom/order.”

So the Great Work becomes:

> **expand and reorganize the human cognitive light cone so the organism is no longer ruled by small defensive sub-agents, but by a higher-order pattern.**

## Your Selfing Loop, Levinized

Your loop:

> generate → repeat → entrench → activate role → identify → act → retrain generation → repeat

Levin’s version:

> local agents form stable goal-loops → those loops recruit lower-level systems → repetition strengthens the pattern → the organism’s agency gets captured by a smaller-scale goal.

So “selfing” is not some ghost inside the head. It is a **scale-collapse**.

The organism could be organized by a wide, integrated intelligence. Instead, under threat/craving/shame, it collapses into a narrow sub-agent:

**Appeaser**
**Seeker**
**Performer**
**Victim**
**Controller**
**Rebel**
**Spiritual special one**

At that moment, the whole body-mind becomes the instrument of a tiny goal. That is bondage.

## Bioelectricity as the body-level mechanism

Levin’s work on bioelectricity gives this a concrete biological analogue. He argues that cells coordinate through bioelectric networks, and that these networks help cellular collectives pursue large-scale anatomical goals such as development, regeneration, and cancer suppression. ([Springer][3])

That matters because it shows something profound:

> **Living matter can be organized by higher-level target patterns.**

A body is not just a pile of parts. It is a collective intelligence whose parts are glued together toward a larger goal. Levin’s “cognitive glue” idea names exactly this: mechanisms that align subunits toward a shared model of self, world, and goal. ([Forms of life, forms of mind][4])

Now translate that into practice:

**Trauma/selfing** = cognitive glue captured by defensive roles.
**Ajahn Lee** = breath re-glues the body as one calm field.
**Kundalini/haṭha** = prāṇa/channel work changes the coordination of the body-field.
**LBRP/Kabbalistic Cross** = symbolic glue organizes the body-space as temple.
**Deity yoga** = the entire system is glued around an enlightened pattern.
**Enochian** = the system is plugged into a specific angelic-symbolic map.

## Predictive perception: the “world” is rendered

Anil Seth’s “controlled hallucination” framing fits your first step: perception is not passive reception. The brain is constantly predicting; sensory input constrains and corrects the prediction. ([thisisyourbrain.com][5])

Friston/active inference gives the formal engine: perception and action are tied together through prediction-error minimization; organisms perceive by updating models and act to bring the world/body into line with predictions or preferred states. ([PMC][6])

So yes:

> **You do not encounter a raw world. You encounter a rendered world shaped by priors, body-state, culture, memory, affect, and action-readiness.**

But I’d slightly correct your wording. It is too strong to say “the organism never contacts the world.” It does contact something — but only **through an adaptive rendering**. The rendering is real as experience, but not identical with reality itself.

That correction matters because it keeps us from drifting into pure solipsism.

## Hoffman adds the dashboard layer

Donald Hoffman’s interface theory says perception evolved for adaptive fitness, not for showing reality as it is. The “Fitness Beats Truth” work supports the idea that perceptual systems guide adaptive behavior rather than providing a veridical representation of objective reality. ([PubMed][7])

That maps perfectly to your role-loop.

The organism doesn’t render:

> “objective situation.”

It renders:

> “threat,” “status,” “rejection,” “food,” “mate,” “danger,” “safety,” “opportunity,” “ritual power,” “divine contact.”

So magical practice is dangerous and powerful because it deliberately modifies the dashboard.

Bad magic: install fantasy icons and believe them literally.
Good magic: re-render the world around a more truthful, integrated, compassionate pattern.

## Dennett: the self is not the controller

Dennett’s “center of narrative gravity” is useful because it removes the fake inner boss. He says the self is like a center of gravity: a useful abstraction, not a physical thing inside the system. ([PhilPapers][8])

That fits your thesis:

> **The self is the loop, not the owner of the loop.**

There is no little “me” behind the appeaser, seeker, magician, meditator, victim, or genius. There are patterns of perception-action-identification that stabilize around a narrative center.

So the spiritual task is not to find the ego-controller.

It is to see the loop forming and stop appropriating it as:

> “I am this.”

## Where Buddhism locks it in

Your Ñāṇananda/Ñāṇavīra point is the precision layer.

A role becomes bondage only when feeling/perception/action is appropriated as:

> **mine / me / I am this.**

The selfing loop does not need a permanent self. It only needs repeated appropriation.

A feeling arises.
Prediction renders it.
A role activates.
Narrative says “this is me.”
Action follows.
Action reinforces the prior.

That is dependent arising as cybernetic feedback.

Kamma becomes:

> **action updating the priors that generate future perception.**

Nibbāna, mechanically, is not the destruction of the organism. It is the failure of step 4:

> rendering no longer gets appropriated as “I am.”

So perception continues. Action continues. Compassion can continue. But the loop no longer closes into selfhood.

## Where magick fits scientifically

Now your occult model becomes very clean.

Magick is not “ego controls universe.”

Magick is:

> **intentional alteration of the generative model through body, breath, symbol, sound, attention, role, ritual, and action.**

In active-inference language, ritual changes priors and preferred states.

In Levin language, ritual reorganizes the agency-structure of the organism.

In Buddhist language, ritual changes conditions.

In Hermetic language, ritual aligns microcosm with macrocosm.

In Vajrayana language, deity yoga replaces ordinary self-world rendering with enlightened body/speech/mind/mandala.

In Enochian language, the angelic OS gives the rendering a formal symbolic address-space.

## So what are “outside influences”?

Here we need subtlety.

A strict scientist would say:

> “These are internally generated models, symbols, and altered states.”

A Kastrup/idealist would say:

> “Since consciousness is primary, these may be contacts across layers of mind.”

A Levin-style bridge would say:

> “The key question is not inside vs outside. The question is: what scale of agency is organizing the system?”

That is the move.

When “Chenrezig” organizes the body-mind, compassion expands the cognitive light cone.

When “Mars” organizes the body-mind, will/conflict/action-patterns dominate.

When “Enochian angelic architecture” organizes the body-mind, perception is routed through that specific symbolic hierarchy.

When the HGA/daimon organizes the body-mind, the life becomes directed by a larger-scale goal than ego-relief.

So “contact” means:

> **a higher-order pattern becomes capable of organizing perception, body-state, speech, and action.**

Whether you call that internal archetype, transpersonal intelligence, angel, deity, daimon, or Platonic pattern depends on metaphysics.

The functional test is the same:

> **What does it organize the organism to become?**

## The full integrated model

Here’s the whole thing in one stack:

**Predictive processing:** perception is generated.
**Hoffman:** the rendering is adaptive, not truth-first.
**Levin:** living systems are nested agents with scale-relative goals.
**Freud/Jung/Lacan/Bourdieu:** roles are affective, symbolic, defensive, cultural, and embodied.
**Dennett:** the “I” is a narrative abstraction, not a controller.
**Buddhism:** bondage begins when the pattern is appropriated as “I am.”
**Kamma:** action reinforces the generative loop.
**Nibbāna:** the loop stops closing around self.
**Magick:** deliberately alters the loop through ritualized perception-action.
**Vajrayana:** installs enlightened rendering while sealing it with emptiness.
**Enochian:** installs a high-complexity angelic interface-map.
**Great Work:** reorganize the organism around the widest, truest, most integrated intelligence available.

## Your metaphysics, made precise

Your earlier model:

> body as receiver, aura as resonance tech, angels/deities as contactable intelligences

Science-grounded version:

> **The body is a multi-scale embodied prediction system. Breath, posture, symbol, sound, and ritual change its generative model and agency-boundaries. This can allow larger-scale patterns — daimonic, archetypal, deity-like, angelic, or transpersonal — to organize the system. The “self” is the stabilized loop of prediction, role, identification, and action. Liberation is seeing the loop before appropriation. Magick is learning to consciously reconfigure the loop without clinging to the new form.**

That is strong.

The final formula:

> **Selfing = unconscious auto-rendering.
> Magick = deliberate re-rendering.
> Tantra = enlightened re-rendering + emptiness.
> Nibbāna = no appropriation of any rendering.
> The Great Work = the body-mind becoming a coherent vessel for the highest-scale pattern, without mistaking that pattern for ego.**

